      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# Roof Segmentation from Satellite Images\n",
        "### dida Test Task\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 1. Problem & Application Context\n",
        "\n",
        "The task is to predict which pixels in a satellite image correspond to rooftops,\n",
        "given 25 labeled image-mask pairs and 5 unlabeled test images to predict on.\n",
        "The labels are binary: white = roof, black = everything else.\n",
        "\n",
        "Looking at dida's project portfolio, particularly their\n",
        "[solar panel planning project with Enpal](https://dida.do/projects/automatic-planning-of-solar-systems)\n",
        "and the accompanying [technical blog post](https://dida.do/blog/semantic-segmentation-of-satellite-images),\n",
        "I believe the main application behind this task is automated solar panel installation planning —\n",
        "specifically, identifying which rooftops are available for panels. This context shaped\n",
        "several of my decisions throughout the notebook:\n",
        "\n",
        "- As I infere from the objective of the project, every roof counts: Small houses, garages, and outbuildings are all potential\n",
        "  solar surfaces, so I tried not to filter or discard small detections\n",
        "- I prioritised **recall over precision**: a missed roof is a missed customer,\n",
        "  while a falsely detected object (e.g. a car) gets caught by the geometric processing (like the post-processing mentioned in dida's website that discards objects that do not pass the geometrical checks)\n",
        "- Some training labels appear noisy: in particular small\n",
        "  houses sometimes miss their labels (e.g. 272.png or 317.png or 324.png). dida acknowledge this challenge in the blog: at production scale 1500 carefully labeled images are used to\n",
        "  average out this noise. With 25 images there is not much I can do about it, but\n",
        "  I note where it likely affects results\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 2. Dataset\n",
        "\n",
        "- 30 satellite RGB images, 256×256 pixels\n",
        "- 25 binary masks (white = roof) for training and validation (note that other than the noise I mentioned above, sometimes the labels are completely wrong, e.g. 278.png in labels, corresponds to 270.png in images.)\n",
        "- 5 unlabeled images as the test set\n",
        "- I used an 80/20 split: 20 images for training, 5 for validation\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 3. Models Considered & Experimental Design\n",
        "\n",
        "I ran four experiments in total, comparing two architectures against two loss\n",
        "configurations, and selected the best-performing combination based on the calculated metrics.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Architecture 1: U-Net — [[Paper]](https://arxiv.org/abs/1505.04597)\n",
        "I started with U-Net as the natural baseline. It was designed for exactly this kind\n",
        "of problem: Pixel-wise segmentation with small training sets. The encoder-decoder\n",
        "structure with skip connections preserves fine spatial detail like roof edges and\n",
        "corners. Furthermore, dida's own production system for this task also uses U-Net,\n",
        "as described in the blog.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Architecture 2: U-Net++ — [[Paper]](https://arxiv.org/abs/1807.10165)\n",
        "U-Net++ improves on U-Net by replacing the direct skip connections\n",
        "with dense nested pathways (intermediate nodes that progressively refine the\n",
        "encoder features before they reach the decoder). In practice this reduces the\n",
        "semantic gap between encoder and decoder at each resolution level and consistently\n",
        "gives considerable IoU points improvement on aerial building segmentation tasks.\n",
        "\n",
        "Both architectures use a **ResNet34 encoder pretrained on ImageNet** as the backbone.\n",
        "With only 20 training images, training a full network from scratch would overfit\n",
        "immediately. The pretrained encoder already understands edges, textures, and shapes\n",
        "from 1.2 million natural images, so we only need to fine-tune it to care specifically\n",
        "about roofs. dida confirm in the blog that transfer learning from ImageNet gave\n",
        "significant improvements.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Loss V1: BCE + Dice | Adam optimizer\n",
        "The baseline loss. Dice was also dida's own confirmed choice for this task. It handles\n",
        "class imbalance naturally without needing manual class weights, unlike cross-entropy.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Loss V2: BCE + Dice + Boundary weighting | Adamax optimizer\n",
        "I considered this variant after visually inspecting the test predictions and\n",
        "noticing some failures (a small house missed entirely, another only partially\n",
        "detected). Since dida explicitly found boundary weighting improved their results, it seemed worth trying a pixel-weighting strategy that adds extra penalty near roof\n",
        "edges to encourage sharper boundaries. Adamax felt appropriate given the label noise in the dataset. The results did not improve for U-Net++ (though this loss did help U-Net) mainly because I think with only 20 noisy training\n",
        "images there simply isn't enough signal for the extra loss term to learn from. I kept it anyways for further possible discussions.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Model Selection\n",
        "After training all four variants I evaluated them both quantitatively and visually.\n",
        "U-Net++ with the baseline loss (V1) came out on top: highest IoU, Dice, and Recall of all four models. I proceeded with **U-Net++ V1** for the final predictions.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 4. Evaluation Metrics\n",
        "\n",
        "I report three metrics on the validation set:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Metric | What it measures |\n",
        "|---|---|\n",
        "| **IoU** | Overlap between predicted and true mask — the standard segmentation metric |\n",
        "| **Dice / F1** | Similar to IoU, slightly more lenient on partial overlaps |\n",
        "| **Recall** | Of all actual roof pixels, how many did I find? |\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 5. Dependencies\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook was developed and tested on Google Colab with a T4 GPU. If running\n",
        "locally, install all dependencies via `pip install -r requirements.txt`. On Colab,\n",
        "only `segmentation-models-pytorch` and `albumentations` need to be installed\n",
        "explicitly, the rest come pre-installed.\n",
