    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Discussion & Conclusions\n",
        "\n",
        "I compared two architectures (U-Net and U-Net++) against two loss configurations\n",
        "(BCE+Dice and BCE+Dice+boundary weighting), training four models in total. U-Net++\n",
        "with BCE+Dice loss and Adam optimizer performed best on the validation set, therefore I used that for the final predictions.\n",
        "\n",
        "The model performs well on most of the 5 test images, correctly identifying the\n",
        "main roof structures. There are some minor failure modes worth noting: missing small houses and misidentifying other objects as roofs. Both of these failure modes are also present in the training labels themselves (see e.g. 270.png, 278.png, 317.png, etc.) This sets a hard ceiling on what any model can achieve regardless of architecture.\n",
        "\n",
        "**What would help most with more time or data:**\n",
        "- More labeled images — this would have a larger impact than any architectural change\n",
        "- Multi-class labels (roof, obstacle, background) as dida use in production, which\n",
        "  would force the model to distinguish cars and chimneys from rooftops explicitly\n",
        "- Cross-validation instead of a single train/val split, which would give a more\n",
        "  reliable performance estimate given the small dataset size"
      ],
